<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,706,1091]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,706,731]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">Monophyly:</emphasis>
Long mistaken as the “ 
<taxonomicName box="[561,704,706,731]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Thiodininae">Thiodininae</taxonomicName>
”, this group is well supported by molecular data (
<figureCitation box="[1260,1348,706,731]" captionStart="FIGURE 36" captionStartId="11.[151,244,1940,1962]" captionTargetBox="[156,1436,383,1912]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[151,1436,371,1919]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURE 36. Summary of molecular phylogeny results. Numbers show likelihood bootstrap percentages, in format &lt;chimera analysis&gt; / &lt;non-chimera analysis&gt; (&lt;analysis without Nilakantha and Gypogyna&gt;)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245749/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">Figs 36</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1359,1389,707,731]" captionStart="FIGURES 37 – 38" captionStartId="16.[151,258,1890,1912]" captionTargetBox="[167,1421,206,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,191,1868]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 37 – 38. Maximum likelikhood phylogenies from Chimera and Non-chimera matrices, combined 5 gene analyses. Numbers show likelihood bootstrap % for Amycoids only; in parenthesis are bootstrap percentages for analysis without Nilakantha and Gypogyna (shown for deep amycoid branches only). Rectangles at nodes indicate bootstrap support in parsimony analysis (filled rectangle at least 75 %; open 50 % to 74 %). Sites partitioned as per PartitionFinder analysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245750/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">37</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 39 – 43" captionStartId="18.[151,258,1806,1828]" captionTargetBox="[168,1425,314,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,299,1785]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 39 – 43. Maximum likelihood phylogenies from analyses on individual genes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245751/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">
39, 41, 
<number box="[195,224,743,767]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" value="43.0">43</number>
</figureCitation>
) and is easily recognized by a series of morphological features, though each of the features is missing in some species of this group. First, most species have two pairs of bulbous setae on the ventral surface of the tibia of the front leg, unique among spiders, thought to enhance sensation for the handling of prey (
<bibRefCitation author="Hill" box="[1210,1326,814,839]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" refString="Hill, D. E. (2012) Notes on the jumping spiders Thiodina puerpera (Hentz, 1846) and Thiodina sylvana (Hentz, 1846) in the southeastern United States (Araneae: Salticidae). Peckhamia, 99.1, 1 - 63." type="journal article" year="2012">
Hill 
<number box="[1265,1326,815,839]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" value="2012.0">2012</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Second, many species have a carapace/femur I stridulatory apparatus (
<bibRefCitation author="Maddison" box="[872,1056,850,875]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" refString="Maddison, W. P. (1987) Marchena and other jumping spiders with an apparent leg-carapace stridulatory mechanism (Araneae: Salticidae: Heliophaninae and Thiodininae). Bulletin of the British Arachnological Society, 7, 101 - 106." type="journal article" year="1987">
Maddison 
<number box="[997,1056,851,875]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" value="1987.0">1987</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), but it is not clear whether this structure evolved on one of the branches within this subfamily or is a synapomorphy reversed in subgroups. Third, most species have a well developed RTA accompanied by a sinuous RvTA in the male palp (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Galiano" box="[1240,1396,922,947]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" refString="Galiano, M. E. (1963) Las especies americanas de aranas de la familia Salticidae descriptas por Eugene Simon: Redescripciones basadas en los ejemplares tipicos. Physis, Revista de la Sociedad Argentina de Ciencias Naturales (C), 23, 273 - 470." type="journal article" year="1963">
Galiano 
<number box="[1336,1396,922,947]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" value="1963.0">1963</number>
</bibRefCitation>
: pl. XL, figs 
<number box="[260,305,959,983]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" value="2.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="1.0">1–4</number>
). The embolus is also articulated with the tegulum by a well-developed hematodocha (
<figureCitation box="[1335,1423,958,983]" captionStart="FIGURES 50 – 52" captionStartId="20.[151,258,1225,1247]" captionTargetBox="[167,1419,208,1192]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,191,1203]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 50 – 52. Morphological characters of Amycoida. 50 divided lorum present in Gophoinae (arrow shows area with thin cuticle). 51 fused lorum (Amycinae), as that present in non-gophoine Amycoida. 52 expanded left male palp (Cotinusa) showing developed distal hematodocha articulating the embolus with the rest of the bulb." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245753/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">
Fig. 
<number box="[1392,1423,958,983]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" value="52.0">52</number>
</figureCitation>
), though whether this is a synapomorphy or a plesiomorphy is unclear.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,706,1091]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">
We note that the molecular results (
<figureCitation box="[635,728,1030,1055]" captionStart="FIGURES 37 – 38" captionStartId="16.[151,258,1890,1912]" captionTargetBox="[167,1421,206,1858]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,191,1868]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 37 – 38. Maximum likelikhood phylogenies from Chimera and Non-chimera matrices, combined 5 gene analyses. Numbers show likelihood bootstrap % for Amycoids only; in parenthesis are bootstrap percentages for analysis without Nilakantha and Gypogyna (shown for deep amycoid branches only). Rectangles at nodes indicate bootstrap support in parsimony analysis (filled rectangle at least 75 %; open 50 % to 74 %). Sites partitioned as per PartitionFinder analysis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245750/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">Figs 37</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[747,776,1031,1055]" captionStart="FIGURES 39 – 43" captionStartId="18.[151,258,1806,1828]" captionTargetBox="[168,1425,314,1772]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[151,1436,299,1785]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURES 39 – 43. Maximum likelihood phylogenies from analyses on individual genes." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245751/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">41</figureCitation>
) support the separation of 
<taxonomicName box="[1109,1234,1030,1055]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Nilakantha" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1109,1234,1030,1055]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">Nilakantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1301,1395,1030,1055]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Colonus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1301,1395,1030,1055]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">Colonus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Bustamante 
<emphasis box="[290,346,1066,1091]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="272">et al.</emphasis>
(
<number box="[361,422,1066,1091]" pageId="21" pageNumber="272" value="2015.0">2015</number>
).
</paragraph>
